1
00:00:02,253 --> 00:00:07,311
I remember
when I first entered a temple,

2
00:00:07,311 --> 00:00:10,037
it was in Haight-Ashbury,
and this temple was called

3
00:00:10,037 --> 00:00:13,163
the Śrī Śrī Rādhā–Kṛṣṇa Temple.

4
00:00:13,163 --> 00:00:19,601
This was in December in 1969,
and around that time

5
00:00:19,601 --> 00:00:27,114
the Śrī Īśopaniṣad was published
by ISKCON Press.

6
00:00:27,207 --> 00:00:28,418
[Eyes to See God]

7
00:00:28,418 --> 00:00:30,702
But I remember one thing
I’d read in that book is,

8
00:00:30,702 --> 00:00:36,301
every evening in China-town

9
00:00:36,301 --> 00:00:41,261
I was having discussions
with a Marxist friend of mine …

10
00:00:42,461 --> 00:00:45,432
And we would have
these discussions

11
00:00:45,432 --> 00:00:51,576
about ‘important things’,
‘deep thoughts’,

12
00:00:53,916 --> 00:00:59,445
but when it came to the God issue,

13
00:00:59,445 --> 00:01:05,100
I was having some difficulty
convincing him. 

14
00:01:05,100 --> 00:01:10,442
And I remember reading in the introduction
to Prabhupad’s Īśopaniṣad,

15
00:01:10,442 --> 00:01:17,112
where it says, “Originally delivered as a
series of lectures at Conway Hall in London”,

16
00:01:17,112 --> 00:01:21,781
Prabhupad in one point said,

17
00:01:21,781 --> 00:01:25,067
as my friend would say,

18
00:01:25,067 --> 00:01:28,653
“Show me God.
Prove that God exists”,

19
00:01:28,653 --> 00:01:33,816
Prabhupad said, “People often ask,
‘Can you show me God?’”

20
00:01:33,830 --> 00:01:36,735
So he had my attention,

21
00:01:36,735 --> 00:01:39,811
and then he said,

22
00:01:39,811 --> 00:01:44,479
“But do you have the eyes 
to see God?”

23
00:01:44,479 --> 00:01:48,390
And I jumped out of my seat
dancing,

24
00:01:48,390 --> 00:01:49,958
I was so happy.

25
00:01:49,958 --> 00:01:53,134
And whether that man

26
00:01:53,134 --> 00:01:55,949
could understand that
or appreciate that

27
00:01:55,949 --> 00:01:58,150
became almost irrelevant.

28
00:01:58,150 --> 00:02:00,292
I was very happy to hear that.

29
00:02:00,292 --> 00:02:04,914
Yes, do you have the eyes
to see God? 

30
00:02:04,914 --> 00:02:09,686
When Srila Saraswatī Ṭhākur
was asked once …

31
00:02:09,686 --> 00:02:14,476
Guru Mahārāj told, some man,
a very serious man

32
00:02:14,476 --> 00:02:18,969
highly educated,
highly positioned in society,

33
00:02:18,969 --> 00:02:21,617
wanted to ask him
a very personal question.

34
00:02:21,617 --> 00:02:24,960
So two chairs were drawn
into a private place

35
00:02:24,960 --> 00:02:26,895
and Guru Mahārāj,

36
00:02:26,895 --> 00:02:31,921
like a Jaimini ṛṣi 
in Bṛhad-bhāgavatāmṛta,

37
00:02:31,921 --> 00:02:35,083
hiding in the bushes
to overhear the conversation of

38
00:02:35,083 --> 00:02:39,436
Parīkṣit and Uttarā,

39
00:02:39,813 --> 00:02:43,556
that man said to Saraswatī Ṭhākur—
their faces got close and he said,

40
00:02:43,556 --> 00:02:47,646
“Have you seen God?”

41
00:02:50,360 --> 00:02:54,817
And Saraswatī Ṭhākur told him,

42
00:02:55,292 --> 00:03:03,251
“You have to learn the culture;
cultivation; how to see God.

43
00:03:03,251 --> 00:03:08,956
Whether I have or haven’t
is irrelevant to your position.

44
00:03:09,197 --> 00:03:16,723
You must learn, culture, cultivate,
this type of seeing.”

45
00:03:17,975 --> 00:03:21,752
So we’re told, 
spiritually speaking,

46
00:03:21,752 --> 00:03:24,133
we learn śāstra-chakṣus;

47
00:03:24,133 --> 00:03:27,012
to see through 
the eyes of scripture.

48
00:03:27,012 --> 00:03:32,108
Conventional seeing 
will not be helpful.

49
00:03:32,295 --> 00:03:40,405
So we want to see
through the eyes of the devotees,

50
00:03:40,405 --> 00:03:44,546
and Guru Mahārāj has given us
such an excellent example:

51
00:03:44,546 --> 00:03:47,148
the telescopic system.

52
00:03:47,148 --> 00:03:50,075
Because normally we think,

53
00:03:50,075 --> 00:03:54,026
“I am here, the seer,

54
00:03:54,026 --> 00:03:59,741
and the object of my vision
is there,

55
00:03:59,741 --> 00:04:07,411
and something intervenes—
it creates opacity, normally.

56
00:04:07,411 --> 00:04:11,269
But if what is intervening

57
00:04:11,269 --> 00:04:16,078
between me and the object
of my vision is a lens,

58
00:04:16,078 --> 00:04:19,892
then not only does it not create opacity,

59
00:04:19,892 --> 00:04:22,313
but it creates clarity.

60
00:04:22,313 --> 00:04:28,366
What may be distant and far,

61
00:04:28,412 --> 00:04:34,260
far beyond what can’t be seen
by the naked eye,

62
00:04:34,260 --> 00:04:39,120
with the lens will be brought 
near and become clear—

63
00:04:39,120 --> 00:04:41,557
come clearly into focus.

64
00:04:41,557 --> 00:04:46,114
So he’s compared the lens,
the eye of devotion.

65
00:04:46,114 --> 00:04:47,866
What we do hear 
in Brahma-saṁhitā?

66
00:04:47,866 --> 00:04:50,487
Premāñjana-chchhurita-bhakti-vilochhanena

67
00:04:50,487 --> 00:04:54,777
santaḥ sadaiva hṛdayeṣu vilokayanti 
(Bs: 5.38).

68
00:04:54,777 --> 00:04:59,101
Those who are seeing Kṛṣṇa,
Kṛṣṇa conception,

69
00:04:59,101 --> 00:05:02,468
if we come under the influence
of their conception;

70
00:05:02,468 --> 00:05:07,673
the lens of their devotional seeing:

71
00:05:07,673 --> 00:05:13,073
who is normally abstract,
unclear, remote,

72
00:05:13,073 --> 00:05:18,246
becomes palpable, accessible,
clearly into focus.

73
00:05:18,246 --> 00:05:21,375
And he said,
“And a series of such lenses

74
00:05:21,375 --> 00:05:23,469
is the telescopic system,

75
00:05:23,469 --> 00:05:25,963
known as the Guru-paramparā.” 

76
00:05:25,963 --> 00:05:35,553
That means we entrust ourselves 
to put ourselves under the guidance

77
00:05:35,553 --> 00:05:45,528
of those who are themselves
under the influence of scripture,

78
00:05:45,528 --> 00:05:49,208
or beyond the influence of scripture,
in the case of the rāga-mārg bhaktas,

79
00:05:49,208 --> 00:05:51,171
but I mean, who sees
through the eyes of scriptures—

80
00:05:51,171 --> 00:05:54,579
Sādhu, Śāstra, Guru and Vaiṣṇava.

81
00:05:54,579 --> 00:05:57,792
That’s how we will see things properly.

